'''Dalongdong''' ({{zh|t=大龍峒|p=dàlóngdòng}}), or '''Toalongpong''' ({{zh|t=大龍泵||poj=Tōa-lông-pōng}}; and variants 大浪泵/大隆同), is an old village in historical [[Taipei]] located nears the narrows of the intersection between the [[Keelung River|Keelung]] and [[Tamsui River]]s. The district has since been merged with the newer [[Twatutia]] district in the south during the [[Qing dynasty]] to form [[Datong District, Taipei|Datong District]].
The village, officially created in 1853 (3rd year of the [[Xianfeng Emperor]]), covered the area extending from the Chen Teacher's abode ({{lang|zh|陳悅記祖宅}}) and beyond the area of ''sishisikan'' (四十四坎) and the [[Taipei Confucius Temple]]. During [[Taiwan under Japanese rule|Japanese rule]], the villages of Twatutia, Toalongpong, and [[Wanhua District|Bangka]] were combined with the [[Walls of Taipeh|walled city of Taipeh]] (in present-day [[Zhongzheng District]]) and incorporated into present-day Taipei city. Although this district now exists only historically, its name still officially remains in the [[Dalongdong Baoan Temple]] and on bus numbers 303 and 669 of the [[Taipei bus|Taipei bus system]].
==Name== Although the history of the village likely preceded [[Dutch Formosa]] rule, its existence was first recorded during this time as '''Pourompon''' (from the [[Basay language]]). This gave rise to the names ''Paronpon'' ({{zh|c=巴浪泵|poj=Pa-lông-pōng|labels=yes}}), ''Daronpon'' ({{zh|c=大龍泵|poj=Toā-lông-pōng|labels=no}})<ref>{{holodict|40034|e=大龍泵}}</ref> and other variants, when the area came under [[Taiwan under Qing rule|Qing dynasty rule]]. The name was once again changed ({{zh|c=大隆同|poj=Toā-liông-tông|labels=no}}) in 1802 (7th year of [[Jiaqing Emperor]]), by settlers from [[Tong'an District]] in [[Xiamen]]. It was during this period that the Baoan Temple was first constructed. The name finally settled in its present form ({{zh|t=大龍峒|labels=no}}) during the reign of the [[Daoguang Emperor]] (1820-1850) when further settlement occurred in the area.
