[[File:Porta San Pellegrino 1.jpg|thumb|right|upright|Porta San Pellegrino]]

'''Porta San Pellegrino''' is a gate in the outer wall of [[Vatican City]]. It is located beside [[Bernini's Colonnade]] and the small Vatican post; it is also known as Porta Viridaria. The gate was rebuilt by [[Pope Alexander VI]] in 1492 and his arms are at the top of the gate. The gate is little used.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://utenti.quipo.it/romeartlover/Vasi41.htm#Porta |title=Basilica di S. Pietro in Vaticano |publisher=Rome in the footsteps of an XVIIIth century traveller |accessdate=31 August 2012 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091124004732/http://utenti.quipo.it/romeartlover/Vasi41.htm |archivedate=2009-11-24}}</ref>

{{Location map | Vatican | caption = Location on a map of Vatican City | float = left | width = 170 | label = Porta San Pellegrino | lat_deg = 41 | lat_min = 54 | lat_sec = 12.6 | lat_dir = N | lon_deg = 012 | lon_min = 27 | lon_sec = 25.74 | lon_dir = E }}

On Friday, February 6, 2015, [[Catholic News Service]] (CNS) reported, in a brief online news release on its website, that the Vatican, through a communique, had announced that it had finished remodeling a public bathroom, to include three showers (which the article stated will be open every day except Wednesday, the day of the Pope's general audience, and other times when there are large events in the Basilica and the Square) and a barber's chair (haircuts will be available on Mondays), near Bernini's Colonnade. The services, which will include issuance of kits for hygiene, are meant for the homeless pilgrims of the Vatican.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.catholicnews.com/data/briefs/cns/20150206.htm#head4 |title=Catholic News Service}}{{dead link|date=August 2015}}</ref>

